{"Title":"When not to use ObjectCloud","Contents":"\n\u003Cp>\u003Ca href=\"about.page\">About ObjectCloud\u003C/a>\u003C/p>\u003Cp>Let's face it. &nbsp;Nothing's perfect. &nbsp;ObjectCloud is very alpha. &nbsp;While it's a wonderful piece of software that saves harmless kittens and makes julian fries; there are some use cases that it's just not designed to handle. &nbsp;This document describes situations where you might be better off with other web development systems.\u003C/p>\u003Ch1>Maturity\u003C/h1>\u003Cp>ObjectCloud is very alpha, therefore, if you're looking for a web development platform that's mature, stable, and bug-free, ObjectCloud probably isn't the best to use.\u003C/p>\u003Ch1>Scalability\u003C/h1>\u003Cp>The trendy thing to do today is to have a single web application hosted in a single place and scale to millions of users.&nbsp; An example is \u003Ca target=\"_blank\" title=\"\" href=\"http://code.google.com/appengine/\">Google App Engine\u003C/a>.&nbsp; The intention with ObjectCloud is to, for the immediate future, target smaller-scale applications that might only have 100-200 users.&nbsp; ObjectCloud scales through decentralization; although future versions of ObjectCloud might be able to handle larger loads.\u003Cbr>\u003C/p>\u003Ch1>Performance\u003C/h1>\u003Cp>No performance testing is performed.&nbsp; Performance improvements are expected in future releases.\u003C/p>\u003Ch1>Stability\u003C/h1>\u003Cp>As ObjectCloud is very alpha, stability is a concern.&nbsp; A primary cause of instability on Windows comes from server-side Javascript.&nbsp; Specifically, ObjectCloud's Javascript environment uses \u003Ca target=\"_blank\" title=\"\" href=\"http://www.mozilla.org/rhino/\">Rhino\u003C/a> running under \u003Ca target=\"_blank\" title=\"\" href=\"http://www.ikvm.net/\">IKVM\u003C/a>.&nbsp; This particular combination tends to cause lots of ugly crashes when hosted on Windows.\u003C/p>\u003Ch1>Server-Side Programming\u003C/h1>\u003Cp>ObjectCloud is designed to minimize server-side programming.&nbsp; One consequence is that ObjectCloud relies more on browser Javascript to render HTML instead of server-side scripting.&nbsp; Web applications that would require a heavy amount of server-side programming are not a good choice for ObjectCloud; unless the server-side programming is intended to extend the object paradigm by adding more core data types.\u003C/p>\u003Cp>At this point, only server-side Javascript is documented.&nbsp; There are ways to add more core data types, proxies, and other complicated .Net code.&nbsp; These are undocumented for now.\u003C/p>\u003Cp>\u003Ca href=\"about.page\">About ObjectCloud\u003C/a>\u003C/p>"}